<br>
Problems I see with taxation:<br>
<br>
1.) Easy to work around, one could have their wares listed in the bazaar interface and when a sale is to be made, simply break trader and sell without a tax.<br>
<br>
2.) Since one could still list their items in the bazaar menu, they'd still be taking up a trader spot from other people, so it wouldn't necessarily reduce crowding significantly.<br>
<br>
3.) Items with low competition would increase by the % of the tax to account for it. Items with high competition would potentially remain the same as players would resort to attempting to undercut and still profit by utilizing /auction instead of the taxed bazaar interface. (I'm no economist, but that's what I'd do, hehe)<br>
<br>
The good points about a bazaar tax would be that leaving your character on for extended periods taking up a trader slot would pose a penalty in the form of the tax on unattended transfers.<br>
<br>
Problems I see with a running deduction:<br>
<br>
1.) In essence it would create a gap of players that are able to utilize the Bazaar, &quot;takes money to make money&quot; I guess.<br>
<br>
I like that it would impose a penalty for taking a trader slot for extended periods.<br>
<br>
I think the spirit of the Bazaar isn't meant to block low level, poor characters from being able to attempt to sell their items, but I also think it wasn't meant for players to leave characters logged on at all times, hogging the available space.<br>
<br>
Regarding that, perhaps a system that limited the amount of time one could remain in trader mode would allow for more people to enjoy its benefits. Determining the amount of time, however, may be awkward. <br>
<br>
One could reason that it could be tied to the level of the player: the higher the level, the longer one is able to stay in-trader (per day, per week, whatever), reducing the effectiveness of the surge of level 1-5 mules created specifically to stand in the Bazaar. This, of course, would favor using one's main as a trader overnight, which in itself would have intrinsic benefits such as decreased merchant anonymity and increased responsibility. Writing this, though, I can only think of &quot;mmm, another time sink!&quot; coming from habitual traders and rare-hunters.<br>
<br>
One could also reason that the amount of time could be based upon how much stuff one is trying to sell. Jeebushepmeh with 80 items up for sale would naturally need more time to offload items than Ogrewhompum who has been online for 5 days straight trying to sell his glowing wooden crook. A downside to this, however, would be that it would promote the use of middle-man merchants, who sell others' items for a portion of the profits, which would reduce the number of traders using slots in the bazaar, but would create more potential scam scenarios and also increase merchant anonymity, possibly even raise prices by reducing sources of competition.<br>
<br>
Hard to say, and either way could come off as unfair to some.<br>
<br>
Renting a spot in the bazaar to determine time may be the best idea, though depending on the rates, it may be exclusionary to lower level characters. Perhaps an increasing rate, starting at so many hours free, but increasing the longer one uses the bazaar on a particular account. If by that point even lower level characters don't make enough to foot another rental, perhaps the bazaar really isn't going to be doing them any good.<br>
<br>
Some thoughts of my own for the Bazaar:<br>
<br>
o.) When a trader runs out of inventory, remove their trader status and move them into the aisle.<br>
---o) When a trader has been removed from the bazaar and remains AFK making it apparent the person is away for an extended period without anything left to sell, the player should be removed from the server to lessen the load on other players.<br>
<br>
o.) Implement a periodic reorganization of the bazaar traders to maximize usage of space, rather than allowing the traders to bunch up on top of one another. Would make things much easier on: shoppers, those just wanting to bank, and other traders who otherwise may not have been clickable due to blockage.<br>
<br>
o.) Implement a client-side filter for the Bazaar only to turn off displaying of all other clients in Trader status. Perhaps apply it to the &quot;Find Trader&quot; mystical path in such a way that the other traders either dim or disappear while the mystical path leads the shopper to their desired trader.<br>
